  "prompt": "How were jobs and responsibilities delegated in Ancient Athens?",
  "response": "In Ancient Athens, jobs and responsibilities were delegated through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. Political Structure\n- Citizens (free adult males) could participate in the democratic assembly\n- Elected officials and public servants were chosen through voting\n- Positions were often selected by lottery to ensure fairness\n\n2. Social Classes\n- Citizens had more political and economic opportunities\n- Slaves performed manual labor and domestic work\n- Metics (foreign residents) could work in trades and commerce\n- Women were generally excluded from public roles\n\n3. Economic Divisions\n- Farmers worked agricultural lands\n- Artisans and craftsmen produced goods\n- Merchants engaged in trade\n- Some citizens owned businesses or held public administrative roles\n\n4. Government Roles\n- Archons managed different aspects of city administration\n- Strategos (military generals) led military operations\n- Council members (Boule) prepared assembly agendas\n- Judges administered legal proceedings\n\n5. Military Service\n- Citizens were expected to serve in military\n- Wealthier citizens typically served as heavily armed hoplite soldiers\n- Poorer citizens might serve in lighter infantry or naval roles\n\n6. Religious Responsibilities\n- Priests and priestesses performed religious ceremonies\n- Citizens participated in various religious festivals and rituals\n\nThe delegation was primarily based on citizenship, wealth, and individual capabilities.",
